        "source_site": "tsa",
        "listing_url": "https://www.tsabusinessschool.co.za/2025/09/17/build-confidence-as-manager",
        "slug": "build-confidence-as-manager",
        "title": "Overcoming Imposter Syndrome: Essential Advice for New and Seasoned Managers",
        "excerpt": "",
        "published_at": "",
        "category": "",
        "featured_image_url": "https://www.tsabusinessschool.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/businessman-using-digital-tablet-1-scaled-1-400x250.jpg",
        "content_html": "<div class=\\"prose prose-lg max-w-none\\"><div class=\\"et_post_meta_wrapper\\">\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<h1 class=\\"entry-title\\">Overcoming Imposter Syndrome: Essential Advice for New and Seasoned Managers</h1>\\n\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p class=\\"post-meta\\"> by <span class=\\"author vcard\\"><a href=\\"https://www.tsabusinessschool.co.za/author/minkie/\\" title=\\"Posts by Eberhard Niklaus\\" rel=\\"author\\">Eberhard Niklaus</a></span> | <span class=\\"published\\">Sep 17, 2025</span> | <a href=\\"https://www.tsabusinessschool.co.za/category/education/\\" rel=\\"category tag\\">Education</a> | <span class=\\"comments-number\\"><a href=\\"https://www.tsabusinessschool.co.za/2025/09/17/build-confidence-as-manager/#respond\\">0 comments</a></span></p><img src=\\"/images/images/blog/businessman-using-digital-tablet-1-scaled-1-1080x675.jpg\\" alt=\\"Businessman using a digital tablet for self-development\\" class=\\"\\" width=\\"1080\\" height=\\"675\\" srcset=\\"/images/images/blog/businessman-using-digital-tablet-1-scaled-1-980x653.jpg 980w, /images/images/blog/businessman-using-digital-tablet-1-scaled-1-480x320.jpg 480w\\" sizes=\\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) 1080px, 100vw\\">\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\"entry-content\\">\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\n<h2 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>Self-doubt plagues leaders at every level\\u2014here\\u2019s how to conquer it and lead with true confidence.</strong></h2>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>Introduction</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Imposter syndrome is a silent struggle that affects even the most successful managers. Whether you\\u2019re stepping into your very first leadership role or you\\u2019ve guided teams for years, persistent doubts about your competency can cloud your achievements. Why does imposter syndrome strike both new and experienced managers? More importantly, how can you move past these doubts to lead authentically and effectively? This article breaks down what imposter syndrome is, why it happens, and\\u2014most critically\\u2014proven strategies for overcoming it and thriving as a leader.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h2 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>A Manager\\u2019s Guide to Building Confidence and Thriving as a Leader</strong></h2>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>What Is Imposter Syndrome?</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Imposter syndrome is the recurring belief that your success is due to luck or external factors\\u2014and that any moment now, you\\u2019ll be \\u201cfound out\\u201d as a fraud. You might think you\\u2019re the only one battling these thoughts, but research reveals up to <strong>70% of professionals</strong> will experience imposter feelings during their careers. This includes respected executives, seasoned managers, and even world-renowned leaders.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Imposter thoughts most often surface during times of change: a promotion, a new challenge, or a high-stakes project. Ironically, these feelings are a sign you\\u2019re growing and stretching your abilities\\u2014not proof that you\\u2019re unqualified.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>Why Both New and Seasoned Managers Feel Like Imposters</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p><strong>New managers</strong> often face self-doubt as they suddenly become responsible for leading others, learn unfamiliar skills, and compare themselves to more experienced colleagues. That inner voice whispers, \\u201cWho am I to lead this team?\\u201d</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p><strong>Seasoned managers</strong> can face imposter syndrome as the stakes rise, teams expand, or the business landscape shifts. The pressure to appear certain and \\u201chave all the answers\\u201d can actually increase self-doubt, with the nagging sense of, \\u201cI should have figured this out by now.\\u201d Remember, <strong>imposter syndrome doesn\\u2019t disappear with experience\\u2014the difference comes in how you manage it</strong>.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<figure class=\\"wp-block-image size-large\\"><a href=\\"https://open.spotify.com/show/5NJrwtsHCiZ61sGR6yq7hp\\"><img fetchpriority=\\"high\\" decoding=\\"async\\" width=\\"1024\\" height=\\"341\\" src=\\"/images/images/blog/2-1024x341.jpg\\" alt=\\"Microphone on desk with notes and laptop, representing TSA Business School podcast on cold calling and sales leadership\\" class=\\"wp-image-3144\\" srcset=\\"/images/images/blog/2-1024x341.jpg 1024w, /images/images/blog/2-980x327.jpg 980w, /images/images/blog/2-480x160.jpg 480w\\" sizes=\\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) 1024px, 100vw\\"></a><figcaption class=\\"wp-element-caption\\">Tune in to the TSA Business School podcast for expert tips on cold calling, leadership, and sales performance.</figcaption></figure>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h2 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>9 Strategies for Overcoming Imposter Syndrome</strong></h2>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>No matter where you are on the leadership journey, these practical strategies help you replace doubt with confidence.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>1. Acknowledge and Normalize It</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Imposter feelings are common\\u2014and they do <strong>not</strong> mean you\\u2019re a fraud. High-achieving figures from Maya Angelou to Einstein have openly discussed their self-doubts. When you talk about it, you\\u2019ll discover how many others feel the same way.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>2. Challenge Negative Self-Talk</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Notice critical thoughts like, \\u201cI\\u2019m not good enough.\\u201d Challenge them: Is this fear, or fact? Reframe \\u201cI was just lucky\\u201d to \\u201cI worked hard\\u2014and it paid off.\\u201d This shift helps you see yourself as others already do: capable and deserving.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>3. Track and Celebrate Successes</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Maintain a \\u201cwins journal\\u201d or file of positive feedback. When self-doubt strikes, look back at your genuine achievements for a reality check and a confidence boost.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>4. Seek Support and Feedback</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Talk about your doubts with trusted mentors or colleagues. Honest feedback helps keep your self-perception balanced. When praised, resist the urge to deflect\\u2014simply accept the compliment.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>5. Embrace Self-Compassion</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Most leaders cheer their teams on but can be harsh critics of themselves. Treat yourself with the same empathy and encouragement you offer others\\u2014self-compassion is a powerful antidote to self-criticism.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>6. Focus on Learning, Not Perfection</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Perfectionism fuels imposter syndrome. Aim for progress, not flawlessness. Mistakes are not proof you\\u2019re a fraud\\u2014they\\u2019re learning opportunities. Expertise takes time and practice.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>7. Set Realistic Goals and Celebrate Progress</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Break big challenges into manageable milestones. Celebrate each step forward\\u2014the path to lasting self-assurance is made up of consistent small wins.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>8. Leverage Visualization and Affirmations</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Visualize yourself succeeding and handling tough situations. Combine this with daily affirmations like \\u201cI am capable\\u201d or \\u201cI bring value\\u201d to reshape your inner narrative over time.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>9. Foster Team Openness</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Encourage your team to discuss challenges openly and celebrate learning. When leaders share their own moments of self-doubt, it normalizes these experiences for everyone, making the whole organization more resilient.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<figure class=\\"wp-block-image size-large\\"><a href=\\"https://thesuccessacademy.co.za/\\"><img loading=\\"lazy\\" decoding=\\"async\\" width=\\"1024\\" height=\\"341\\" src=\\"/images/images/blog/office-rentals-in-pretoria2-1024x341.jpg\\" alt=\\"\\" class=\\"wp-image-3160\\" srcset=\\"/images/images/blog/office-rentals-in-pretoria2-1024x341.jpg 1024w, /images/images/blog/office-rentals-in-pretoria2-980x327.jpg 980w, /images/images/blog/office-rentals-in-pretoria2-480x160.jpg 480w\\" sizes=\\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) 1024px, 100vw\\"></a></figure>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h2 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>For Organizations: Creating a Culture That Reduces Imposter Syndrome</strong></h2>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Leaders can do even more by shaping an environment where feedback, recognition, and vulnerability are encouraged. Mentorship programs, regular wellness check-ins, and openly acknowledging that even leaders have doubts\\u2014all create a safer, stronger workplace. When staff feel safe admitting struggles, everyone grows together.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>Moving Forward With Confidence</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Imposter syndrome doesn\\u2019t disappear overnight; you manage it by recognizing doubts when they arise\\u2014and consistently focusing on your growth and achievements. The objective isn\\u2019t to never feel self-doubt, but rather to make sure it never holds you back from leading and evolving.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h3 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>You\\u2019ve earned your seat at the table; your unique skills and experiences make a real difference.</strong></h3>\\n\\n\\n\\n<h4 class=\\"wp-block-heading\\"><strong>Conclusion: You\\u2019re Not Alone\\u2014and You\\u2019re Not an Imposter</strong></h4>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>If you\\u2019re wrestling with self-doubt as a manager, remember: you\\u2019re in good company. The best leaders aren\\u2019t those who never experience anxiety\\u2014they\\u2019re those who move forward anyway. Recognize your wins, reframe your thinking, lean on your supporters, and embrace your strengths. Your career, your team, and your organization will all reap the benefits of your courage.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n<p>Ready for more leadership resources and practical growth strategies? For tailored development programmes and coaching, visit TSA Business School at <a href=\\"http://www.tsabusinessschool.co.xn--zaunlock-2n3d/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener\\">www.tsabusinessschool.co.za\\u2014unlock</a> the confident leader within you today!</p>\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\"et_post_meta_wrapper\\">\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\n\\n<section id=\\"comment-wrap\\">\\n\\t\\t   <div id=\\"comment-section\\" class=\\"nocomments\\">\\n\\t\\t  \\n\\t\\t  \\t   </div>\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<div id=\\"respond\\" class=\\"comment-respond\\">\\n\\t\\t<h3 id=\\"reply-title\\" class=\\"comment-reply-title\\"><span>Submit a Comment</span> <small><a rel=\\"nofollow\\" id=\\"cancel-comment-reply-link\\" href=\\"/2025/09/17/build-confidence-as-manager/#respond\\" style=\\"display:none;\\">Cancel reply</a></small></h3><form action=\\"https://www.tsabusinessschool.co.za/wp-comments-post.php\\" method=\\"post\\" id=\\"commentform\\" class=\\"comment-form\\"><p class=\\"comment-notes\\"><span id=\\"email-notes\\">Your email address will not be published.</span> <span class=\\"required-field-message\\">Required fields are marked <span class=\\"required\\">*</span></span></p><p class=\\"comment-form-comment\\"><label for=\\"comment\\">Comment <span class=\\"required\\">*</span></label> <textarea id=\\"comment\\" name=\\"comment\\" cols=\\"45\\" rows=\\"8\\" maxlength=\\"65525\\" required=\\"required\\"></textarea></p><p class=\\"comment-form-author\\"><label for=\\"author\\">Name <span class=\\"required\\">*</span></label> <input id=\\"author\\" name=\\"author\\" type=\\"text\\" value=\\"\\" size=\\"30\\" maxlength=\\"245\\" autocomplete=\\"name\\" required=\\"required\\"></p>\\n<p class=\\"comment-form-email\\"><label for=\\"email\\">Email <span class=\\"required\\">*</span></label> <input id=\\"email\\" name=\\"email\\" type=\\"text\\" value=\\"\\" size=\\"30\\" maxlength=\\"100\\" aria-describedby=\\"email-notes\\" autocomplete=\\"email\\" required=\\"required\\"></p>\\n<p class=\\"comment-form-url\\"><label for=\\"url\\">Website</label> <input id=\\"url\\" name=\\"url\\" type=\\"text\\" value=\\"\\" size=\\"30\\" maxlength=\\"200\\" autocomplete=\\"url\\"></p>\\n<p class=\\"comment-form-cookies-consent\\"><input id=\\"wp-comment-cookies-consent\\" name=\\"wp-comment-cookies-consent\\" type=\\"checkbox\\" value=\\"yes\\"> <label for=\\"wp-comment-cookies-consent\\">Save my name, email, and website in this browser for the next time I comment.</label></p>\\n<p class=\\"form-submit\\"><input name=\\"submit\\" type=\\"submit\\" id=\\"submit\\" class=\\"submit et_pb_button\\" value=\\"Submit Comment\\"> <input type=\\"hidden\\" name=\\"comment_post_ID\\" value=\\"3847\\" id=\\"comment_post_ID\\">\\n<input type=\\"hidden\\" name=\\"comment_parent\\" id=\\"comment_parent\\" value=\\"0\\">\\n</p><p style=\\"display: none !important;\\" class=\\"akismet-fields-container\\" data-prefix=\\"ak_\\"><label>\\u0394<textarea name=\\"ak_hp_textarea\\" cols=\\"45\\" rows=\\"8\\" maxlength=\\"100\\"></textarea></label><input type=\\"hidden\\" id=\\"ak_js_1\\" name=\\"ak_js\\" value=\\"207\\"></p></form>\\t</div><!-- #respond -->\\n\\t\\t</section>\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</div></div>",
